{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585714"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:16:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:16:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15005"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15005"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0,0.91,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66743"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7693"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52197"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18802"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66743"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDifferent classes of antibiotics have distinct mechanisms of action that target various bacterial cellular components and processes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotic classes targets bacterial cell wall synthesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aminoglycosides","Macrolides","Beta-lactams","Rifamycins","Quinolones"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-lactams\u003C/strong\u003E, which inhibit bacterial cell wall synthesis by binding to penicillin-binding proteins (PBPs). These proteins are essential enzymes involved in peptidoglycan cross-linking during cell wall assembly. Without proper cell wall synthesis, bacteria become osmotically unstable and lyse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other antibiotic classes work through different mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAminoglycosides\u003C/strong\u003E bind to the 30S ribosomal subunit and inhibit bacterial protein synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrolides\u003C/strong\u003E bind to the 50S ribosomal subunit to inhibit protein synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERifamycins\u003C/strong\u003E inhibit bacterial RNA synthesis by binding to DNA-dependent RNA polymerase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuinolones\u003C/strong\u003E prevent DNA replication by inhibiting DNA gyrase and topoisomerase IV\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these distinct mechanisms of action is crucial for predicting antimicrobial spectrum, clinical use, and potential resistance mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Beta-lactam antibiotics work by inhibiting bacterial cell wall synthesis through binding to penicillin-binding proteins","Each major antibiotic class has a unique mechanism of action targeting specific bacterial cellular processes","Understanding antibiotic mechanisms helps predict their spectrum of activity and potential resistance patterns"],"references":["Zhou J, Cai Y, Liu Y, An H, Deng K, Ashraf MA, Zou L, Wang J. Breaking down the cell wall: Still an attractive antibacterial strategy. Front Microbiol. 2022 Sep 23;13:952633. doi: 10.3389/fmicb.2022.952633. PMID: 36212892; PMCID: PMC9544107.","Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","